<div class="description">
	<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color: white;color: #333333;font-size:14px;" width="100%"><tbody><tr><td style="border:0;padding:0px;"><div style="max-width: 800px;margin:0 auto;"><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="margin:0 auto;border-spacing:0;border-collapse: collapse !important;" width="100%"><tbody>
<tr><td style="border:0;padding:10px;background-color: #ffffff;"><img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/ps-feeds-production/inline_images_1551483008023-OPUSD-Masthead-1600x400.jpg" alt="alt_text" border="0" style="width: 100%;max-width: 800px;height: auto;"></td></tr>
<tr><td style="border:0;padding:10px;font-size: 14px;color: #333333;">Good Morning,<br><br>I think we can all agree that the honeymoon phase has come to an end. Lack of routine and normalcy is catching up to most of us and our children as well. As a parent, I have seen some habits forming just in these past three weeks. My children are staying up (and waking up) later than I would like. They miss their friends and their extracurricular activities. I want you to know that OPUSD understands the effort it is taking for staff, parents, and students to adjust and complete Distance Learning tasks and assignments. We are equally concerned about ensuring the social and emotional well being of our students. Please note our staff and administration is here to support you, please don't hesitate to reach out as we are here to help. To that end, I want to take this opportunity to share a few critical areas to help support your children through this challenging time.<br><br><u>Communicate:</u> Talking to children about this public health crisis is challenging. As parents, we are our children’s first insight into what is happening in our world. Keep talking to your children about the effects of their “new normal” and listen to their concerns. Do not share your panic or fears when speaking to children about COVID-19. Always present age-appropriate facts, and do so calmly and confidently, so they feel secure with your words. Here are some suggestions from the CDC and Child Mind Institute on how to support your children:<br><br><ul>
<li>
<a class="fr-strong" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/talking-with-children.html" target="_blank">Take time to talk with your child or teen</a> about the COVID-19 outbreak.</li>
<li>Answer questions and <a class="fr-strong" href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/share-facts.html" target="_blank">share facts about COVID-19</a> in a way that your child or teen can understand.</li>
<li>Reassure your child or teen that they are safe. Let them know it is ok if they feel upset. Share with them how you deal with your own stress so that they can learn how to cope from you.</li>
<li>Limit your family’s exposure to news coverage of the event, including social media. Children may misinterpret what they hear and can be frightened about something they do not understand.</li>
<li>Try to keep up with regular routines. If schools are closed, create a schedule for learning activities and relaxing or fun activities.</li>
<li>Be a role model. Take breaks, get plenty of sleep, exercise, and eat well. Be understanding of frustration over not seeing friends (try scheduling virtual playdates or time to hang out with friends). </li>
<li>Support remote schooling</li>
<li>Help them practice mindfulness.</li>
<li>Validate their disappointment</li>
<li>Encourage healthy habits - Fuel for the Body/Mind. </li>
<li>Emphasize social distancing. </li>
<li><a class="fr-strong" href="https://www.palipost.com/ask-bbb-36/" target="_blank">Additional tips/article for younger children</a></li>
</ul>
<br><u>Plan Activities:</u> It helps children if you can mix up the daily routine at home so as to avoid perseverating on excessive anxiety or worry:<br><br><ul>
<li>Enjoy some family time (movie nights, board games, puzzles, cards, etc.) </li>
<li>Move your body. </li>
<li>Clear your mind (yoga, guided meditations, calming music) </li>
<li>Practice kindness (write thank you notes to community helpers, make a gratitude list, give compliments, etc.) </li>
<li>Video chats, calls, and messages with friends and family. </li>
<li>Cook or bake a fun recipe. </li>
<li>Have an indoor picnic. </li>
<li>Have an at-home spa day or self-care day.</li>
</ul>
<p style="margin:0;"><img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/ps-feeds-production/inline_images_1586538908166-Screen+Shot+2020-04-10+at+10.14.44+AM.png" style="width: 300px;display: block;vertical-align: top;margin:5px auto 5px 0px;text-align: left;"></p>I highly suggest signing up for <a class="fr-strong" href="https://childmind.org/coping-during-covid-19-resources-for-parents/" target="_blank">Child Mind Institute</a> Daily <a class="fr-strong" href="https://signup.e2ma.net/signup/1917784/1800565/" target="_blank">tips and emails</a><br><br><u>Behavior Changes:</u><br>Listed below are some tips/suggestions for parents to watch for when observing behaviors in children during this challenging time. Please note, not all children and teens respond to stress in the same way, but there are some common behavior changes of which you should be aware of. These behaviors do not automatically point to a bigger problem, but consistent patterns of these behaviors could be of concern.<br><br><ul>
<li>Excessive crying or irritation in younger children</li>
<li>Returning to behaviors they have outgrown (for example, toileting accidents or bedwetting)</li>
<li>Excessive worry or sadness; isolation</li>
<li>Unhealthy eating or sleeping habits</li>
<li>Irritability and “acting out” behaviors in teens</li>
<li>Poor school performance or avoiding school</li>
<li>Difficulty with attention and concentration</li>
<li>Avoidance of activities enjoyed in the past</li>
<li>Unexplained headaches or body pain</li>
<li>Use of alcohol, tobacco, or other drugs</li>
<li>Reluctance to exercise and be active</li>
</ul>Our Counselors are here for your students. If you would like to speak to your counselor about academic or social-emotional needs, here is their contact information:<br><br><strong>Brookside</strong> - Sam King (<a class="fr-strong" href="mailto:sking@opusd.org">sking@opusd.org</a>)<br><strong>Oak Hills</strong> - Alana Schulman (<a class="fr-strong" href="mailto:aschulman@opusd.org">aschulman@opusd.org</a>)<br><strong>Red Oak</strong> - Holly Baxter (<a class="fr-strong" href="mailto:hbaxter@opusd.org">hbaxter@opusd.org</a>)<br><strong>Medea Creek -</strong><div style="margin-left:20px;">Dianne Large (Last Names A-F) (<a class="fr-strong" href="mailto:dlarge@opusd.org">dlarge@opusd.org</a>)</div>
